<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-03-22T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-03-22T14:00:00-05:00" n="1365" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1365">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/1621</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the</hi>
                            <gloss type="to">
                                <hi rend="italic">Secretary of State</hi>
                            </gloss>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-03-22T20:00:00+01:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">March 22, 1915, 8 p. m.</hi>
                                </date>
                                <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received March 23, 5.40 p.
                                m.</hi>]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>1891. Your 1360, March 12, 5 p. m. The German Government does not share
                            apprehensions of danger to foreigners in Turkey in view of the composure
                            with which Turkish people have hitherto viewed the attacks on the
                            Dardanelles, but the German Ambassador at Constantinople has been
                            informed of the apprehensions of the American Government and instructed
                            to use his influence in the desired direction should occasion arise.
                            German Government convinced that Turkish Government would of its own
                            accord take measures to protect non-combatants not of Moslem faith in
                            the event of danger to their lives and property.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_GJW1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Gerard</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>